<subsection xml:id="subsec-trigonometric-ratios-of-special-angles">
    <title>Trigonometric ratios of special angles((30°, 45° and 60°))</title>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            Trigonometry helps us understand the relationship between the angles and sides of a right-angled triangle. 
            Some angles are special because their trigonometric values 
            are easy to remember and frequently used in math and science. These special angles are <m>30^\circ,\, 45^\circ, \,\text{and}\, 60^\circ</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            As we discussed earlier, the trigonometric ratios still apply in this situation as; 
        </p>
        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow> sin\,\theta=\amp \frac{\text{Opposite}}{\text{ Hypotenuse}} </mrow>
                <mrow>cos\,\theta =\amp \frac{\text{Adjacent }}{\text{Hypotenuse}}</mrow>
                <mrow> tan\,\theta=\amp \frac{\text{Opposite}}{\text{Adjacent }}</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            The trigonometrical ratios of <m>30^\circ,\, 45^\circ, \,\text{and}\, 60^\circ</m> 
            can be deduced by the use of an
            isosceles right-angled triangle and an
            equilateral triangle as follows.
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>\textbf{Note:}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <term>Isosceles</term> trangle are trianglse whose 2 sides and the base angles are equal.
                    </p>

                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <term>Equilateral triangle </term> are triangle whose sides and angles are equal.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </introduction>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-Tangent-cosine-and-Sine-of-45">
        <title>Tangent, Cosine and Sine of 45°</title>
        <p>
            In this section we use isosceles right-angle triangle to explore on how to find Tangent, Cosine and Sine of <m>45^\circ</m>
        </p>
        <activity>
            <p>
                <m>\textbf{Work in groups}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>What you require:</term> A ruler, a piece of paper and a protractor.
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Draw the isosceles right-angle triangle like the one below,(ensure that two sides are equal)
                        </p>
                        <image width="50%">
                        <latex-image label="Triangle17">
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[blue]
                                % Define points
                                \coordinate (R) at (0,0);
                                \coordinate (Q) at (4,0);
                                \coordinate (P) at (4,4);

                                % Draw triangle
                                \draw [very thick,fill=green] (R) -- (Q) -- (P) -- cycle;
                                
                                % Mark right angle at Q
                                \draw (Q) ++(-0.3,0) -- ++(0,0.3) -- ++(0.3,0);

                                % Label points
                                \node[left] at (R) {R};
                                \node[right] at (Q) {Q};
                                \node[above] at (P) {P};

                                % Draw angle arc at R
                                \draw (R) ++(0.5,0) arc[start angle=0, end angle=45, radius=0.5];
                                \node[right] at (0.4,0.3) {$\theta$};
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                           
                        </image>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Measure the angle that substend the Hypotenues and the adjacent that is <m>\theta</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Measure the length <m>PQ \, \text{and}\, QR</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            What do you notice about <m>PQ \, \text{and}\, QR</m>
                        </p>
                        
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the following trigonometrc ratios:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>tan \, \theta</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>cos \, \theta</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>sin \, \theta</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Compare the value of <m>cos \, \theta \, \text{and} \,sin \, \theta </m>, How do they relate?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </activity>
        <p>
           <m>\textbf{Essential concepts}</m> 
        </p>
        <p>
            Look at the figure below;
        </p>
        <image width="50%">
        <latex-image label="Triangle18">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                % Define points
                \coordinate (R) at (0,0);
                \coordinate (Q) at (4,0);
                \coordinate (P) at (4,4);

                % Draw triangle
                \draw [very thick,fill=cyan] (R) -- (Q) -- (P) -- cycle;
                
                % Mark right angle at Q
                \draw (Q) ++(-0.3,0) -- ++(0,0.3) -- ++(0.3,0);

                % Label points
                \node[left] at (R) {R};
                \node[right] at (Q) {Q};
                \node[above] at (P) {P};

                % Draw angle arc at R
                \draw (R) ++(0.5,0) arc[start angle=0, end angle=45, radius=0.5];
                \node[right] at (0.4,0.3) {$45^\circ$};
                
                \node[below] at (2,-0.2) {\(1\)};
                \node[right] at (4,2) {\(1\)};
            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
            
        </image>
        <p>
            <term>Notice that;</term> For an isosceles right-angle triangle, the two sides and the base angles are equal.
        </p>
        <p>
            It implies that, For the special angle of <m>45^\circ</m>, To find the 
            tangent, cosine and sine, find first the length <m>PR</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow> PR^2=\amp 1^2+1^2 </mrow>
                <mrow>= \amp 1+1 </mrow>
                <mrow> =\amp 2</mrow>
                <mrow> PR=\amp \sqrt{2}</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            Therefore,
        </p>
        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow> Sin\,45^\circ=\amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} </mrow>
                <mrow> Cos\,45^\circ=\amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}</mrow>
                <mrow> Tan\,45^\circ=\amp 1</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        
        
    </subsubsection>
    
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-Tangent-cosine-and-Sine-of-30-60">
        <title>Tangent, Cosins and Sine of 30° and 60°</title>
        <p>
            In this section, you will be using equilateral triangle to find the Tangent, Cosine and Sine of <m>30^\circ \, \text{and}\, 60^\circ</m> .
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>\textbf{Work at home}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            Use the same procidure above to identify the Tangent, Cosine and Sine of <m>30^\circ \, \text{and}\, 60^\circ</m> using equilateral triangle.
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>\textbf{Essential concepts.}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            The figure below shows an equilateral triangle <m>ABC</m>. <m>AD</m> Is the perpendicular bisector of
            <m>BC</m>.
        </p>
        <image width="50%">
        <latex-image label="Triangle19">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                % Define points
                \coordinate (A) at (0,4);
                \coordinate (B) at (-3,0);
                \coordinate (C) at (3,0);
                \coordinate (D) at (0,0);

                % Draw the triangle
                \draw [thick, red] (B) -- (A) -- (C) -- cycle;
                
                \draw [fill=green] (B)--(D)--(A)--cycle;
                
                \draw [fill=blue] (D)--(A)--(C)--cycle;
                
                % Draw altitude from A to D
                \draw [thick, red] (A) -- (D);

                % Mark right angle at D
                \draw (D) ++(-0.3,0) -- ++(0,0.3) -- ++(0.3,0);

                % Label points
                \node[above] at (A) {\textbf{A}};
                \node[left] at (B) {\textbf{B}};
                \node[right] at (C) {\textbf{C}};
                \node[below] at (D) {\textbf{D}};

                % Draw angle arcs
                \draw (B) ++(0.5,0) arc[start angle=0, end angle=30, radius=0.9];
                \draw (C) ++(-0.5,0) arc[start angle=180, end angle=150, radius=0.9];
            

                % Label angles
                \node [right]at (-2.5,0.5) {\(\mathbf{60^\circ}\)};
                \node [left]at (2.5,0.5) {\(\mathbf{60^\circ}\)};
                \node [below]at (-0.5,3) {\(\mathbf{30^\circ}\)};
                \node [below]at (0.5,3) {\(\mathbf{30^\circ}\)};

                % Label sides
                \node[left, blue] at (-1.5,2) {\(\mathbf{2}\)};
                \node[right, blue] at (1.8,2) {\(\mathbf{2}\)};
                \node[below, blue] at (-1.5,-0.2) {\(\mathbf{1}\)};
                \node[below, blue] at (1.5,-0.2) {\(\mathbf{1}\)};
                \node[left,below, blue] at (0,-0.7) {\(\mathbf{2}\)};
                
                \draw [&lt;-&gt;,below, blue,very thick](-3,-0.7)--(3,-0.7);
            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
            
        </image>
        <p>
            <term>Notice that;</term>
        </p>
        <p>
            length <m>AD</m> is given by,
        </p>
        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow> AD^2=\amp 2^2-1^2</mrow>
                <mrow>= \amp 4-1</mrow>
                <mrow>AD= \amp \sqrt{3} </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            Therefore, <m>sin\,30^\circ=\frac{1}{2},\quad cos\,30^\circ=\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2},\quad \text{and} \quad tan\,30^\circ=\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            Similarly,
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>sin\,60^\circ=\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2},\quad cos\,60^\circ=\frac{1}{2},\quad \text{and} \quad tan\,60^\circ=\sqrt{3}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <term>Conclusion</term>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Sin and Cos are just swapped between <m>30^\circ </m> and <m>60^\circ </m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Tan <m>30^\circ </m> is small while tan <m>60^\circ </m> is large.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>sin\,\theta \times sin \, \theta </m>, can be written as <m>sin^2\,\theta</m> 
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>

